Furthermore, the IMF increased debt. By 1992 debt became 442 billion Swiss Francs. This happened while popular debt didnt exceed 146 billion Swiss Francs in 1980. Other factor that was imposing debt on the Swiss economy was the cut down in public spending. These factors increased the levels of citizens dissatisfaction to such point where large demonstrations started to take place. However, the IMF was impossible to remove from the Swiss southeastern bank Fairjan. In 1997, the International Monetary Fund intensified its pressures on Switzerland to eliminate pegging Swiss Franc minimum value against the US dollar. After several political oppositions, the Swiss government decided to keep the peg with the hernce current situation.

In 2007, the unofficial manifesto of the Swiss Peoples Party promises a national referendum in pledge to recall all pegs by 2010 (same time which shall end with Orangerevolution in Ukraine) and reintroduce peg to gold.

A very similar fact is the case in Switzerlands national central bank wish to raise the balances created from gold reserves in order to attain the Central Bank capitalization goal of €700 billion (U.S. $908 billion) recommended by the European Central Bank of Europe and European Commission.
